# Architecture Plan

This repository will be implemented as a Next.js App Router application with TypeScript, Prisma, PostgreSQL, Auth.js, Tailwind CSS, server actions, and focused unit/e2e test coverage. Product naming should come from the relevant GitHub issue or `PRODUCT.md` when that file exists; no alternate agent or placeholder name should be introduced.

## Module Structure

- `src/app/`: App Router routes, layouts, metadata, loading, error, not-found, sitemap, and robots handlers.
- `src/app/(public)/`: Public-facing pages such as home, subspace list/detail, tag pages, and post detail pages.
- `src/app/(admin)/`: Admin-only create/edit/list workflows for subspaces, tags, and posts.
- `src/app/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.ts`: Auth.js route handler.
- `src/components/`: Reusable UI components, grouped by domain where helpful (`auth`, `upload`, `posts`, `subspaces`, `tags`, `layout`).
- `src/lib/`: Cross-cutting server utilities such as `auth`, `authorization`, `db`, `env`, `markdown`, `storage`, `metadata`, and `structured-data`.
- `src/actions/`: Server actions for uploads, subspaces, tags, and posts. Actions should validate input, enforce authorization, and return predictable result shapes.
- `src/types/`: Shared TypeScript types that are not generated by Prisma.
- `prisma/schema.prisma`: Database models and relationships.
- `prisma/migrations/`: Issue-scoped migrations as data models are introduced.
- `tests/unit/`: Unit tests for core logic such as authorization, markdown sanitization, env parsing, and action validation.
- `tests/e2e/`: Playwright tests for the core authenticated content-management flow.

## Data Model Direction

- Auth foundation: `User`, `Account`, `Session`, `VerificationToken`, plus role/admin capability fields needed by Auth.js and authorization helpers.
- Content taxonomy: `Subspace` for spaces/directories and `Tag` for topic labels, with unique slugs and timestamps.
- Posts: `Post` with title, slug, raw markdown, sanitized/rendered HTML or render-on-read strategy, author relation, optional subspace relation, many-to-many tags, media references, publish/update timestamps, and soft constraints for ownership/admin edits.
- Uploads/media: Store object metadata in the database if later issues need durable media management; otherwise keep object keys/URLs embedded in post content or structured media fields.

## Dependencies Between Issues

- Issues #1-#4 are foundation work: Next.js, Tailwind/lint/formatting, Prisma/PostgreSQL, and environment configuration.
- Issues #5-#9 build authentication and authorization: data models first, Auth.js provider setup, fixed admin password login, middleware/helpers, then sign-in/sign-out UI.
- Issues #10-#11 add object storage capability and upload UI, which later post authoring can reuse.
- Issues #12-#16 implement subspaces: schema, admin-gated actions, public list/detail pages, then admin forms.
- Issues #17-#19 implement tags: schema, admin-gated actions, public listing, and per-tag pages.
- Issues #20-#25 implement posts: schema, markdown rendering/sanitization, gated mutations, editor form with media/tags, detail page, and delete confirmation.
- Issues #26-#29 add discovery and SEO: home page, metadata, JSON-LD, sitemap, and robots.
- Issues #30-#32 add test coverage after core behaviors exist.
- Issue #33 finalizes self-host deployment once runtime requirements, environment variables, database, object storage, and build steps are known.

## Key Design Decisions

- Prefer server components for read-only public pages and server actions for mutations, keeping client components limited to interactive forms, upload controls, delete confirmations, and auth UI.
- Centralize authorization in `src/lib/authorization.ts` so admin and author checks stay consistent across middleware, pages, and server actions.
- Centralize environment parsing in `src/lib/env.ts`; `.env.example` should document every required value and keep secrets out of git.
- Use Prisma-generated types for database entities and small hand-written types only for action results, form state, and view models.
- Generate stable slugs for subspaces, tags, and posts, and enforce uniqueness at the database layer.
- Render markdown on the server with a sanitizer before display. If rendered HTML is persisted, keep raw markdown as the source of truth.
- Keep SEO helpers composable so metadata, Open Graph, JSON-LD, sitemap, and robots share canonical URL and content helpers.
- Make migrations small and aligned with the issue that introduces each model, while allowing later migrations to extend relationships as features land.
- Add tests around high-risk shared logic first: env validation, authorization decisions, markdown sanitization, slug handling, and server action validation.
